What that means in practice
---------------------------

You can use, study, modify, and distribute OASIS for any purpose, including
academic research (self-funded, grant-funded, institutional, whatever), as
long as you keep this notice and the LICENSE file with the code.

If you modify OASIS and run the modified version as a network service that
other people can interact with (a hosted SaaS deployment, a public demo, a
shared lab instance that participants from other institutions use, etc.),
the AGPL requires you to publish the complete source code of your
modifications under the same AGPL-3.0 license to all users of that service.
This is what stops a commercial vendor from forking OASIS, slapping a
paywall on it, and never giving anything back. Self-hosting OASIS for your
own organisation's internal use does not trigger this requirement.

If you build something useful on top of OASIS (a new provider integration,
a pipeline improvement, a research-specific feature), please consider
contributing it back upstream rather than maintaining a private fork. The
project is much better off when improvements land in the main repo where
everyone benefits. Pull requests are welcome.

Citation
--------

Citation is appreciated but not legally required. If you use OASIS in
published research, please cite the project (BibTeX entry and DOI are in
the README). And please link to the canonical repository
(https://github.com/oasis-surveys/oasis-platform), not a fork.

